13,000 runners expect to compete in the Boston Marathon on April
15th. The course is a jagged 26 miles and 385 yards from Hopkinton,
MA, to downtown Boston. Five miles into the race, a runner can waste
energy charging up a set of little hills. A steep descent into Newton
Lower Falls can jar runners' bones. After a long column of trees comes
Heartbreak Hill, and finally the Haunted Mile, a stretch where many
runners have collapsed. The race is covered by TV from start to finish
and offers a total of $402,000 in prize money. Winners get a medal and
$55,000.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d28"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="SJMN91-06105230"
SELECTOR="E"
SUMMARIZER="H">  

The last three Boston marathons have turned into reckless speed duels,
producing five of the top 10 times in the race's history and becoming
races of attrition. Last year all 11 checkpoint records were shattered
through the first 20 miles. The winner last year was Gelindo Bordin in
2:8:19. He ran a patient, calculating race and passed everyone at 21
miles. The historic route begins west of Boston in Hopkinton and ends
in Copley Square in Boston's Back Bay section. Competitors this year
have also run in the Olympics, the 1990 Commonwealth Games, and the
New York City and London marathons.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d28"
TYPE="PERDOC"
